   A base drawing can be converted to dashed lines.  Moreover, lines can
be made either thin or thick.

   тАв Select the rectangular area you want to operate on (with mouse drag
     or тАШS-<left>тАЩ, тАШS-<down>тАЩ and so on as described earlier).
   тАв Type тАШINSтАЩ, then тАШsтАЩ (as "style").

   You will be offered a choice of styles:
   тАв тАШ3тАЩ: vertical lines will become 3 dashes per character, while
     horizontal ones will get 2 dashes per character.
   тАв тАШ4тАЩ: vertical and horizontal lines will get 4 dashes per character.
   тАв тАШhтАЩ: thin lines corners, which are usually rounded, become hard
     angles.
   тАв тАШ+тАЩ: thin lines and intersections become thick, empty glyphs get
     filled.
   тАв тАШ-тАЩ: thick lines and intersections become thin, filled glyphs are
     emptied.
   тАв тАШ=тАЩ: thick and thin lines become double lines.
   тАв тАШ0тАЩ: come back to standard base-line тАШUnilineтАЩ style: plain,
     not-dashed lines, thin corner rounded, ASCII art is converted to
     UNICODE.
   тАв тАШaтАЩ: apply the тАШaa2u-rectangleтАЩ function from the unrelated
     тАШascii-art-to-unicodeтАЩ package, to convert ASCII art to UNICODE
     (this only works if тАШascii-art-to-unicodeтАЩ is already installed).

   Converting parts of a drawing from one style to another can produce
nice looking sketches.




