==============




     this.text.surrounds      this.text.surrounds
     .                 /      .тЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТ/
     .                //тХ╢тФАтФАтФАтЦ╖тХ┤.тЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТ//
     ...            ////      ...тЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТтЦТ////
       ...a.hole/////           ...a.hole/////


   A hollow shape is a contiguous region of identical characters (not
necessarily blank), surrounded by a boundary of different characters.
The end of the buffer in any direction is also considered a boundary.

   Put the cursor anywhere in the hole.  Then type:

   тАШ<insert> iтАЩ

   Answer by giving a character to fill the hole.

   If instead of a character, тАШSPCтАЩ or тАШDELтАЩ is typed, then a shade of
grey character is picked.  тАШSPCтАЩ selects a darker grey than the one the
point is on, while тАШDELтАЩ selects a lighter.  There are 5 shades of grey
in the UNICODE standard: тАШ" тЦСтЦТтЦУтЦИ"тАЩ.  Those grey characters are well
supported by the suggested fonts.

   тАШC-yтАЩ is also an option.  The first character in the top of the kill
ring will be chosen as the filling character.  (The kill ring is filled
by functions like тАШC-kтАЩ or тАШM-wтАЩ, unrelated to тАШUnilineтАЩ).

   Typing тАШ<return>тАЩ or тАШC-gтАЩ aborts the filling operation.

   A rectangular shape may also be filled.
   тАв Mark a region
   тАв тАШ<insert> iтАЩ
   тАв answer which character should be used to fill.

   There is no limit on the area to fill.  Therefore, the filling
operation may flood the entire buffer (but no more).


