10.1 Recommended fonts
======================

Not all fonts are born equal.

   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "DejaVu Sans Mono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Unifont" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Hack" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "JetBrains Mono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Cascadia Mono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Agave" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "JuliaMono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "FreeMono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Iosevka Comfy Fixed" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Iosevka Comfy Wide Fixed")тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Aporetic Sans Mono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Aporetic Serif Mono" )тАЩ
   тАв тАШ(set-frame-font "Source Code Pro" )тАЩ

   Those fonts are known to support the required UNICODE characters, AND
display them as mono-space.  There are fonts advertised as mono-space
which give arbitrary widths to non-ASCII characters.  That is bad for
the kind of drawings done by тАШUnilineтАЩ.

   You may want to try any of the suggested fonts.  Just hit the
corresponding entry in the тАШUnilineтАЩ menu, or type тАШ<insert> fтАЩ.  You
may also execute the above Lisp commands like that:

   тАШM-: (set-frame-font "DejaVu Sans Mono")тАЩ

   This setting is for the current session only.  If you want to make it
permanent, you may use the тАШEmacsтАЩ customization:

   тАШ<insert> f *тАЩ

   or

   тАШM-x customize-face defaultтАЩ

   Beware that тАШEmacsтАЩ tries to compensate for missing UNICODE support
by the current font.  тАШEmacsтАЩ substitutes one font for another,
character per character.  The user may not notice until the drawings
done under тАШEmacsтАЩ are displayed on another text editor or on the Web.
Of course, using the suggested fonts and the UNICODEs drawn by тАШUnilineтАЩ
keeps you away from those glitches.

   To know which font тАШEmacsтАЩ has chosen for a given character, type:

   тАШC-u C-x =тАЩ

   Note that none of those commands downloads a font from the Web.  The
font should already be available.


